{{Redirect|Wanya language|the Papuan language|Sowanda language}} {{Infobox language |name=Wanyä |altname=Muchi |states=[[Laos]] |region= |ethnicity= |speakers=? |date= |ref= |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Lolo–Burmese languages|Lolo–Burmese]] |fam4=[[Loloish languages|Loloish]] |fam5=[[Southern Loloish languages|Southern]] |fam6=Sila |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Wanyä''' ([[wikt:Autonym|autonym]]: ''{{IPA|wa11 ɲə11}}''; also called '''Muchi''') is a [[Loloish language]] of northern [[Laos]]. It is spoken in Ipoeching village, [[Boun Tay District|Bun Tay District]], [[Phongsaly Province]] (Shintani 2001).
==Classification== Wanyä is a [[sister group|sister]] of the [[Sila language (Laos)|Sila]] cluster of languages that includes [[Sila language (Laos)|Sila]], [[Khir language|Khir]], [[Cosao language|Cosao]], [[Paza language|Paza]] (Phusang), and [[Phana’ language|Phana’]] (Bana).<ref name="Hsiu2016">Hsiu, Andrew. 2016. ''[https://www.academia.edu/26948836/The_classification_of_Cosao_a_Lolo-Burmese_language_of_China_and_Laos The classification of Cosao: a Lolo-Burmese language of China and Laos]''. Presented at the 22nd Himalayan Languages Symposium, Guwahati, India.</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}} * [[Shintani Tadahiko|Shintani, Tadahiko]], Ryuichi Kosaka, and Takashi Kato. 2001. ''Linguistic Survey of Phongxaly, Lao P.D.R.'' Tokyo: Institute for the Study of Languages and Cultures of Asia and Africa (ILCAA).
